DR. SARAH CHEN (42), lead researcher, stands next to a prototype battery unit.

DR. CHEN
(to camera)
What makes this battery different is the material we're using. Instead of lithium, we're using a compound derived from seawater - something that's abundant, cheap, and environmentally friendly.

[B-ROLL: Close-up of battery components, chemical processes]

DR. CHEN (V.O.)
Our tests show this battery can store three times more energy than current lithium-ion batteries, and it can hold that charge for up to six months without significant degradation.

CUT TO:

INT. NEWS STUDIO - EVENING

JESSICA
(to camera)
Three times more energy storage - that's significant. But Dr. Chen says the real breakthrough is in the cost.

CUT TO:

